Introduction

Iâll be looking into a dataset containing the top 2000 movies on IMDb by rating. This dataset contains these variables:

Movie.Name: Name of the movie

Release.Year: Year the movie released

Duration: Length of the movie in minutes

IMDB.Rating: Rating on IMDb

Metascore: Metascore Rating

Votes: Number of votes

Genre: Genre(s) of movie

Director: Person who directed the movie

Cast: Main actor or actress in the movie

Gross: Amount of money that the movie has made

I will be exploring the ratings of movies. FIrst, Iâll explore the correlation between IMDb ratings and Metascore. Then, Iâll look into how some specific movie attributes might affect or predict ratings, such as the movieâs genre and the director of the movie. Finally, Iâll take a look into the correlations between the other numerical variables in our dataset and the ratings.

movies <- read.csv("imdb_top_2000_movies.csv")

IMDB Rating vs Metascore

Letâs take a look into the IMDB Rating and how it compares to the Metascore rating for each particular movie. Letâs start by taking a quick look at the general statistics of each column

stats_no_na <- na.omit(movies)
imdb_stats <- summary(stats_no_na$IMDB.Rating)
metascore_stats <- summary(stats_no_na$Metascore)

stats <- data.frame(
  Variable = c("IMDb Ratings", "Metascores"),
  Mean = c(imdb_stats["Mean"], metascore_stats["Mean"]),
  Median = c(imdb_stats["Median"], metascore_stats["Median"]),
  Min = c(imdb_stats["Min."], metascore_stats["Min."]),
  Max = c(imdb_stats["Max."], metascore_stats["Max."])
)

kable(stats, format = "markdown")

Metascores 60.60481 61 9.0 100.0 
rating <- na.omit(movies)
ggplot(rating, aes(x = IMDB.Rating, y = Metascore)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "IMDb Rating", y = "Metascore") +  
  ggtitle("IMDb Ratings vs. Metascores")

As you can see, there appears to be a positive relationship between IMDb Rating and Metascore. In general, it seems that as one increases, so does the other. But itâs not exactly easy to figure out by how much just by looking at this. Letâs create a linear regression model that will show us the line of best fit for this data.

model <- lm(Metascore ~ IMDB.Rating, data = rating)
slope <- coef(model)[2] #get slope of line

ggplot(rating, aes(x = IMDB.Rating, y = Metascore)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +  
  labs(x = "IMDb Rating", y = "Metascore") +  
  ggtitle("IMDb Ratings vs. Metascores")

correlation_coefficient <- cor(rating$IMDB.Rating, rating$Metascore, method = "pearson")

Now, we can see clearly that there is a positive relationship. The slope of the regression line is 14.6896309 , which represents the rate of change in Metascore for an IMDb rating increase of 1. In other words, when IMDb Rating increases by 1, Metascore increases by 14.6896309. On top of this, we can calculate something called the correlation coefficient to check the strength of the linear relationship. With a correlation coefficient of 0.7509058, there is a strong positive linear relationship with these variables.

Now, letâs take a look at some of the highest rated movies in each metric, to determine how much agreement there is for the best movies.

top_imdb <- head(movies[order(movies$IMDB.Rating, decreasing = TRUE), ], 50)

Now that weâve taken a look at the correlation between IMDB score and Metascore, letâs take a look into what factors specifically might inform these ratings, starting with genre.

Genre

# split genre column 
genre <- movies |>
  mutate(Genre = strsplit(Genre, ", ")) |>
  pivot_longer(cols = Genre, values_to = "Genre") |>
  unnest(cols = Genre) |>
  select(-name)

genre_summary <- genre |>
  group_by(Genre) |>
  summarise(
    mean_imdb = mean(IMDB.Rating, na.rm = TRUE),
    med_imdb = median(IMDB.Rating, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_meta = mean(Metascore, na.rm = TRUE),
    med_meta = median(Metascore, na.rm = TRUE),
    total = n()
  ) |>
  arrange(desc(total))

We can see that IMDB ratings tend to have a lower spread overall by genre than Metascore. Most genres tend to live around the same spot in each graph, as well, with Film-Noir, Documentary, Western, and War all being placed at the top in both. However, it is important to note that both Film-Noir and Documentary had a sample size of under 20, with documentary having just 2.

Directors

Letâs take a look at the directors now. Weâll start by creating 2 datasets for each Metascore and IMDB rating, and then summarizing the ratings for each director. Weâll only include directors who have done 5 or more total movies as to not skew results so much

imdb_director_summary <- movies |>
  na.omit() |>
  group_by(Director) |>
  summarise(
    Mean_Metascore = mean(Metascore, na.rm = TRUE),
    Median_Metascore = median(Metascore, na.rm = TRUE),
    Mean_IMDb_Rating = mean(IMDB.Rating, na.rm = TRUE),
    Median_IMDb_Rating = median(IMDB.Rating, na.rm = TRUE),
    Total_Movies = n()
  ) |>
  filter(Total_Movies >= 5) |>
  arrange(desc(Total_Movies)) 

metascore_director_summary <- movies |>
  na.omit() |>
  group_by(Director) |>
  summarise(
    Mean_Metascore = mean(Metascore, na.rm = TRUE),
    Median_Metascore = median(Metascore, na.rm = TRUE),
    Mean_IMDb_Rating = mean(IMDB.Rating, na.rm = TRUE),
    Median_IMDb_Rating = median(IMDB.Rating, na.rm = TRUE),
    Total_Movies = n()
  ) |>
  filter(Total_Movies >= 5) |>
  arrange(desc(Total_Movies))

Unlike genre, thereâs quite a bit of difference between the IMDB ratings and Metascores. It seems as though many directors appear in both charts, however, just in significantly different spots. For instance, Christopher Nolan is second for the IMDb ratings, but 14th for Metascore!

Letâs take a look now at the comparison between these directorsâ mean Metascore and mean IMDb rating.

imdb_director_summary |>

imdb_lm <- lm(Mean_Metascore ~ Mean_IMDb_Rating, data = imdb_director_summary)
imdb_slope <- summary(imdb_lm)$coefficients[2, 1]

Letâs take a look at the slope: 15.710334 . As weâd expect, this slope is very similar to overall slope of the IMDb rating vs Metascore correlation slope of 14.6896309.

Numerical Data Correlations

Now, letâs take a look at the numerical columns and see if we can find any correlation between pure numerical data and ratings.

correlation_df <- movies
correlation_df$Votes <- as.integer(gsub("[^0-9]", "", movies$Votes))
correlation_df$Gross <- as.integer(gsub("[^0-9]", "", movies$Gross))
correlation_df$Release.Year <- as.integer(gsub("[^0-9]", "", movies$Release.Year))

correlation_df <- na.omit(correlation_df)

imdb_correlation <- cor(correlation_df[, c("Release.Year", "Duration", "IMDB.Rating", "Metascore", "Votes", "Gross")])

metascore_correlation <- cor(correlation_df[, c("Release.Year", "Duration", "IMDB.Rating", "Metascore", "Votes", "Gross")])

print(imdb_correlation["IMDB.Rating", ])
Release.Year     Duration  IMDB.Rating    Metascore        Votes        Gross 
 -0.36438006   0.35695674   1.00000000   0.75090577   0.46967285   0.05899162 
print(metascore_correlation["Metascore", ])
Release.Year     Duration  IMDB.Rating    Metascore        Votes        Gross 
 -0.40342281   0.25116862   0.75090577   1.00000000   0.29913378   0.05210275

As we can see, there arenât really any strong correlations between any of these variables and the ratings. As weâd expect, the release year isnât necessarily indicative of rating, and is in fact negatively correlated. Nor is the Gross, which is actually a bit surprising to me. In fact, the column with the most correlation is Votes and Duration (apart from the other rating value, which weâve already looked at). Overall, though, I donât think any of these are very indicative of what rating the movie will receive.
